      Carlyle's literary career flourished with the publication of "Sartor
      Resartus" in 1833-34, a unique blend of philosophy, satire, and
      autobiography that initially met with mixed reception but later gained
      critical acclaim. His subsequent works, including "The French Revolution"
      (1837), "On Heroes, Hero-Worship, and the Heroic in History" (1841), and
      "Past and Present" (1843), solidified his reputation as a leading
      intellectual figure of the Victorian era. These works, characterized by
      their distinctive style and profound social and political commentary,
      continue to be studied and debated by scholars and readers alike.
